601 praefectorum, ἀο. ‘ his curbed, moderate authority when he held the office oi vicar-im has the lasting tribute (the saeuus, interest paid, on his invest- ment oi good conduct in governing was the good will of the governed) of great affection,’ i.e. the moderation with which he exercised the office of vicarius won a lasting tribute of affection from those over whom he ruled.

Zumpt, who explains frenata as qesta, administrata, fails to give the strict sense oi frenata, which, however, it would seem, is required in order to give much point to the following line. It was not the mere holding of the office, but the holding ot it with moderation and sels-restraint, that won the lasting affection of the governed.

The passages quoted by Zumpt in support of his explanation of jrenata labour under the disadvantage oi not containing the verb frenare, but reqere, moderari, gubernare, which are only remotely applicable.

Zumpt says the vicarii are regularly said aqcre vicem praefectorum, Amm. Marcell. 15, 4, 10; or aqere vices praefectorum, Theod. cod. 2, 33, 1 and 16, 10, 2; Cassiod. Var. 11, 43 and vice praefectorum cognoscere, Theod. Cod. 11, 30, 16.
